translate caption: ["âš ï¸BUYERS IN COSTUMESâš ï¸ Let's start from the assumption that it's summer. Every few years, the swimwear model changes and that's ok. translate caption: ["Today, after all the crawling things, there's a cat's snout. That's the snout of my ex-cat Loki. ex-hangover? Yes, after a small accident we thought it would be better if he moved. Long story short: on Christmas, exactly the 24th, my mother came to visit with her dog. Loki is actually a peaceful guy, so we wanted to see if it worked out tonight. But now she came a little earlier and the cat was still in the house. So I stayed with him. When he saw the dog he started to growl and I picked him up (stupid mistake). Then (because Havanese can't bark) the dog coughed and Loki went nuts. He knew neither friend nor foe and before he caught my big one, I wanted to kick him out. He bit my hand and punctured it in 21 places. Since you shouldn't joke with cat bites, I immediately went to the emergency room - believing that after a short treatment of the wound I would be home for presents. NOPE. I was in the OR at 9 p.m. The next day, despite immediate antibiotics, I had blood poisoning. My hand had 3 surgeries in one week for the infection. That's how long I stayed in the hospital. The good thing: On the day I was discharged, my wife came to the maternity ward and contrary to the corona regulations, since I came directly from the ward, I was allowed to be there as a partner from the beginning, just like in a normal birth. There but then we were unsure about the baby and had seen how quickly things would become dramatic, Loki moved to my sister, where he now has a very happy life with 3 other conspecifics. See for yourself: But what does this teach us? Don't touch a crazed hangover, and if you do, don't joke around with cat bites. It can be life threatening. However, I still love animals. And when the kids are bigger, a pet is definitely not out of the question. I quickly got along with Loki again after that."]

Caption: "The principal planning strategy of the new building was to create a household from a hierarchy of rooms with different amenities placed around a shared common space with multiple purposes, behind a common front door. This created a household with a sense of belonging to the common space and a greater sense of personal responsibility to it and encourages students out of their rooms and into the common space. It also meant a household could be vertically composed of students with various university experiences, creating small communities with a social structure more aligned with the indigenous idea of Kinship.Central to the buildingâ€™s cultural understanding is the creation of the Banksia form, an open four-storey structure centrally located at the confluence of the building and campus networks, veiled in expanded mesh and green vegetation, and creating a counterpoint to the rigidity of the more institutional adjacent buildings. On the ground and first floor, the Banksia is a bleacher seat forum, the second level is the central external social learning and reflection space, and the top is an externally open but shrouded cultural ceremony space with a fire and smoking pit. The dominant form imposes itself on the College creating a significant landmark that reinforces the cultural importance of the facility.": Wilson Architects  : Douglas Mark Black

Caption: Like the state of Alabama has two kinds of music, country and western, it seems we have two kinds of wrens. The Bewicks and the Carolina. Carolina Wrens are more reddish-brown above and pale cinnamon below whereas Bewick's Wrens are browner above and grayish below. Their ranges overlap only in a limited part of the central U.S.Carolina Wrens are largely resident, and will only disperse beyond their range after mild winters. Permanent breeding locations range from eastern Nebraska, southern Michigan, southeast Ontario and the New England states to Mexican states such as Coahuila, Nuevo LeÃ³n, San Luis PotosÃ­ and Tamaulipas and the Gulf Coast of the United States.Bewicks Wrens are now extremely rare east of the Mississippi River.
